# How to build CPython in Debian


### Prerequisites
- Python dependencies
- wget
- tar


### Steps

1. Enable and install source packages in `/etc/apt/sources.list`

    ```bash
    deb http://deb.debian.org/debian trixie main
    deb-src http://deb.debian.org/debian trixie main

    deb http://security.debian.org/debian-security trixie-security main
    deb-src http://security.debian.org/debian-security trixie-security main

    # optional, if you want to get the latest versions
    deb http://ftp.debian.org/debian trixie-backports main
    deb-src http://ftp.debian.org/debian trixie-backports main
    ```

    Then, update and upgrade using `apt`

    ```bash
    sudo apt update -y
    sudo apt upgrade -y
    ```

2. Once source packages are updated, you can now install build dependencies

    ```bash
    sudo apt build-dep python3
    sudo apt install pkg-config
    ```

3. Download your preferred CPython source code

    ```bash
    wget https://www.python.org/ftp/python/3.12.12/Python-3.12.12.tar.xz
    ```

4. Unzip tar file

    ```bash
    tar -xf Python-3.12.12.tar.xz
    cd Python-3.12.12
    ```

5. Run `./configure`

    ```bash
    ./configure
    ```

6. Build using `make`
    
    ```
    make -j8 
    ``` 

    `-j8`, utlizing our CPU cores for faster building

    Once the build succeeds, you will see the following:

    ```
    The following modules are *disabled* in configure script:
    _sqlite3

    The necessary bits to build these optional modules were not found:
    _bz2                  _ctypes               _ctypes_test
    _curses               _curses_panel         _dbm
    _gdbm                 _hashlib              _lzma
    _ssl                  _tkinter              _uuid
    nis                   readline              zlib
    To find the necessary bits, look in configure.ac and config.log.

    Could not build the ssl module!
    Python requires a OpenSSL 1.1.1 or newer

    Checked 111 modules (31 built-in, 63 shared, 1 n/a on linux-x86_64, 1 disabled, 15 missing, 0 failed on import)
    ```

7. Run `python` that you built

    ```bash
    $ .\python
    Python 3.12.12 (main, Feb 28 2026, 09:20:00) [GCC 14.2.0] on linux
    Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
    >>> 
    ```

You may install the python version that you built as follows:

`make install` - this will be installed as your main Python version

`make altinstall` - this will install it separately without overriding your main Python version


